http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10room.html	Room to Improve - New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 Simplicity goes a long way toward making a bathroom feel as if it is from another time. The most difficult part of the job may be undoing old decorating. Before you bring in new fittings, fixtures or furniture, take stock of what you have and remove ill-conceived flourishes. Vinyl flooring or carpet? Rip it out. Jaunty wallpaper? Tear it off. Skip to next paragraph If the tile is white, glossy and clean, you should leave it alone; that is the look you want. If it is colored or printed with images of seahorses, you have little choice but to replace it. As Barbara Sallick, co-founder and senior vice president of design at Waterworks, the high-end bathroom fixtures company, points out, “There are only a few things you can do if you’re stuck with a bubblegum-pink bathroom.” Once you have a relatively clean canvas, you can shift your attention to fixtures and fittings. The most important area is the sink. If you do nothing else, Ms. Sallick said, paint the base of the existing vanity white, replace the counter with a marble slab and install a new basin and fittings. If you have a run-of-the-mill metal medicine cabinet, she said, replace it with a wood unit like the Traditional Medicine Cabinet ($815 to $865) from Waterworks ( ) or the Cartwright Medicine Cabinet ($229 to $329) from Restoration Hardware ( Robin Standefer and Stephen Alesch, the principals of Roman and Williams ( ), a New York design firm, suggested replacing the old vanity unit with a washstand that leaves the plumbing exposed. They installed such a washstand for a client in Los Angeles, with a custom Industrial Base, above, from Urban Archaeology (starting at $1,670 at Where to put items you were storing under the sink? Ms. Standefer and Mr. Alesch suggested building shallow cabinets into the wall. For their client, they created mirrored units above the sinks, surrounded by floor-to-ceiling storage. Ms. Standefer recommended using a high-gloss paint, Hollandlac Brilliant from Fine Paints of Europe ($95 for 2 ½ liters or 2/3 gallon, ), in a cream color on all the woodwork to make it look “instantly sparkly, rich, shiny and washable.” That is important, Mr. Alesch said, because “old-school bathrooms look like you could scrub them down with a bucket of bleach and a huge brush.” When you are choosing hardware, don’t be afraid to buy taps that are separate from the faucet. The one-piece units that many remodelers use, Ms. Sallick said, “are so awful, and so telltale inexpensive.” Use a three-piece set instead, like the ones from the Waterworks Astoria line (from $985). It might also be worth visiting P. E. Guerin (212-243-5270 or ) at 23 Jane Street in Manhattan, one of the oldest decorative hardware manufacturers in the country. Prices for classic stock fittings, like the Beaded Group, start at about $2,000, and custom work is available as well. Glass dispensers like Restoration Hardware’s Grafton Clear Accessories ($39 to $49) and Sabon’s bath products ( ), which come in attractive glass containers, will help create a sense of luxury. Also, make sure your towels are inviting. “Ultimately, there is nothing as luxurious and old-world as beautiful towels hung really neatly on the towel bars,” Ms. Sallick said. Questions about décor may be sent by e-mail to . Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. Next Article in Home & Garden (4 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. PERSONAL HEALTH; A Simple Need, All Too Often Unmet The Year Without Toilet Paper Coming to Madison Square Park: Relief at a Quarter a Flush POSSESSED; Bathroom Reading, On the Wall Next Article in Home & Garden (4 of 9) &#x00bb; A complete guide to summer movies, including critics' picks and a release schedule 5 actors to watch this summer Up close with indie star Parker Posey "The Simpsons Movie" trailer Find home & garden professionals in your area today In Home & Garden: View all Home & Garden Classifieds Post Your Ad Now! Monterey, Where Kids and Sea Lions Play Vendors’ Removal Restores a Gem In the Big House ... Just Visiting Haberman: The Right to a Defense The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10qna.html?ex=1336449600&en=04a178ced821ab47&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Garden Q.&A. - New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 Why are all my rhododendrons browning and looking lame? It’s not just my previously robust specimens; they’re fading all over Westchester County, N.Y. Make that all over the Northeast and beyond, where winter burn is affecting evergreens including rhododendrons, hollies and boxwoods. Last winter, warmth that lasted until January prevented plants from going dormant and increased water needs. Then the thirsty, tender plants were abruptly hit by fierce cold. Unprotected ground froze quickly, so no more water could penetrate. Leaves further dried by sun and wind turned brown. The branches are probably healthy, so prune only as needed for fullness and flowering. Your rhododendrons may also have shoot blight or dieback, said Bradley H. Roeller, manager of grounds and display gardens at the Institute of Ecosystem Studies in Millbrook, N.Y. Winter burn hits mostly the outer foliage, and although the leaves are brown they look otherwise normal, Mr. Roeller said. But if entire branches have deformed brown leaves, even deep within the plant, suspect contagious disease. Wait for a dry, windless day so spores do not spread, he advised. Then prune off all diseased branches, dipping the pruners in isopropyl alcohol to sterilize them between cuts. Can Neem Do It All? I keep hearing that neem is an organic gardener’s cure-all, deadly to pests and diseases but harmless to everything else. Can this be true? No. But it is not far off. Many foliage feeders are repelled by products derived from the tropical neem tree, and those eating neem-covered leaves often lose appetite and starve. Most of neem’s pesticidal punch comes from the compound azadirachtin, which disrupts insects’ growth as well as dampening their appetite. It can also be a fungicide. Used as directed, neem is harmless to mammals and birds, and little danger to beneficial insects. But it is bad for fish. And it usually requires frequent reapplication: the gardener must be an active partner for neem to deserve its sterling reputation. Sources for neem include Peaceful Valley Farm and Garden Supply, (888) 784-1722 or , and Extremely Green Gardening Company, Address questions by e-mail to . Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. Next Article in Home & Garden (5 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Polly Hill Is Dead at 100; Tested Hardiness of Plants IN THE GARDEN; Must Tulips Wither as the Climate Changes? IN THE GARDEN; A Tree-Hugger Shows Her Affection With a Saw Next Article in Home & Garden (5 of 9) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard Narcotic Maker Guilty of Deceit Over Marketing Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Movie Review | '28 Weeks Later': The Satire Is Biting, and So Are the Zombies Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Prenatal Test Puts Down Syndrome in Hard Focus Chevron Seen Settling Case on Iraq Oil President Open to Benchmarks in Iraq Measure Gonzales Seems Confident He Will Stay, Officials Say Kansas Tornado Renews Debate on Guard at War Facebook to Offer Free Classifieds 6 Men Arrested in a Terror Plot Against Ft. Dix A Sweet So Sour: Kool-Aid Dills Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » A complete guide to summer movies, including critics' picks and a release schedule 5 actors to watch this summer Up close with indie star Parker Posey "The Simpsons Movie" trailer Find home & garden professionals in your area today In Home & Garden: View all Home & Garden Classifieds Post Your Ad Now! Monterey, Where Kids and Sea Lions Play Vendors’ Removal Restores a Gem In the Big House ... Just Visiting Haberman: The Right to a Defense The New York Times Company
