http://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/26/garden/26WEBtour.html?ex=1335240000&en=828def00bda5df6d&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	House tours-garden tours-show houses - New York Times For the Curious, It’s Open House Season Properties open to the public this year will include a modernist home overlooking the Hudson River in Garrison, N.Y., owned by Joe Chapman, the former companion of the designer Russel Wright. Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: April 26, 2007 The 2007 season of show houses and house and garden tours runs through fall, with several events every weekend. Skip to next paragraph Fifteen private gardens in brownstone Brooklyn. Visitors — dreamers, planners, would-be master builders and just plain oglers — can peer into rooms that have been painstakingly restored to period detail, fancifully concocted with the latest whimsy and stuffed with owners’ collections of artworks great and knickknacks small. They can gaze at the flowers, trees, mosses, grasses, ferns and fountains that have transformed backyards into seasonal Edens, smell the scent of blooms and feel the soft breezes. Here, starting in New York City, are all manner of house tours, show houses and garden tours. Unless otherwise noted, each is self-guided. MANHATTAN, THROUGH MAY 22 The 35th annual Kips Bay Decorator Show House is open in a 1904 Beaux-Arts mansion built by C.P.H. Gilbert, at 14 East 82nd Street. The participants include 20 designers; Monica Rich Kosann, a portrait photographer; and three painters. The show house is open Monday through Saturday, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. (until 8 p.m. on Tuesdays and Thursdays), and Sundays, noon to 5 p.m. No children under 6. Tickets, to benefit the Kips Bay Boys and Girls Club, $30. More information: (718) 893-8600, extension 245 and BROOKLYN HEIGHTS, MAY 12 Five houses will be open from 1 to 5 p.m. in this neighborhood, which was designated New York’s first historic district in 1965. One is a former carriage house built in 1846 and converted to residential use 100 years later. It is decorated with Biedermeier, Asian and American antiques, and its garden features a brick folly surrounded by weeping cherry trees and rose bushes. A Renaissance Revival house overlooking the East River and the Manhattan skyline, and an 1833 wooden Federal house that has just been restored also will be featured. No children under 13 except infants in front packs. Reservations are recommended for tickets, $30, at (718) 858-9193 and . On the day of the tour only, tickets will be sold starting at 12:30 p.m. at 129 Pierrepont Street (near Clinton Street). PARK SLOPE, BROOKLYN, MAY 20 Eight houses will be open from noon to 5 p.m. during the 48th annual edition of the Park Slope Civic Council house tour, along with the St. Francis Xavier Church, a Gothic Revival building designed by Thomas Houghton, which will be open from 1:15 to 5 p.m. Guided tours will be offered in the church, which features a rose window and the only known stained glass window based on a Peter Paul Rubens painting. The houses on the tour include a 1909 neo-Italian Renaissance home decorated with African dowry objects and a collection of prints and paintings; a 1903 Arts and Crafts style house with Mission furniture, several chandeliers and an unusual split staircase; and an 1895 converted carriage house with an interior courtyard. No children under 10 except infants in front packs. Tickets are $25, at Eighth Avenue and Garfield Place. Advance tickets, $20, and information: (718) 832-8227 and HAMILTON HEIGHTS, MANHATTAN, JUNE 3 Ten to twelve houses will be open from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. On June 2 at 11 a.m., there will be a guided walking tour in the neighborhood. Tickets for June 3, $25, at Hamilton Grange National Monument, Convent Avenue at 141st Street. Tickets for the guided tour on June 2 are $15. Information: (212) 281-4442 and PROSPECT LEFFERTS GARDENS, BROOKLYN, JUNE 3 Eight houses and the garden of a local landscape designer will be open from noon to 5 p.m. The properties include a three-story 1904 brownstone which is decorated with the owners’ collection of 19th- and 20th-century Asian and English antiques, with front and backyard gardens, a greenhouse, large spa-like baths and a children’s playroom. There is also a contemporary renovation inside a 1906 house damaged by fire in the 1970s, with a slate bathroom suite featuring cascading water and a skylight, a stainless-steel kitchen and a music room. A 98-year-old restored limestone row house with its original parquet floors and plaster ceilings and moldings is accented by such salvaged artifacts as a marble back-splash from the Biltmore Hotel, and mahogany doors from the onetime AT&T building, which have been made into a desk. Infants in front packs only. Tickets, $25, at Mike’s International Restaurant, 552 Flatbush Avenue (Maple Street). Advance tickets, $20, and information: (718) 284-6210 or (718) 462-0024; by e-mail to PROSPECT HEIGHTS, FORT GREENE AND CLINTON HILL, BROOKLYN, JUNE 3 At least 15 private gardens will be open from 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. for the 10th annual Brownstone Brooklyn Garden District’s Garden Walk. They include a children’s play garden; two “endangered” gardens, which are within the footprint of the proposed Atlantic Yards development; and a double garden surrounding a brick cottage. There will also be several community gardens, planted with vegetables, flowers, herbs and ornamentals. Tickets, $20, at the Forest Floor, 659 Vanderbilt Avenue (Prospect Place) in Prospect Heights; at the Brooklyn Academy of Music garden, Lafayette Avenue at St. Felix Street in Fort Greene; and at Tillie’s, DeKalb and Vanderbilt Avenues in Clinton Hill. Advance tickets, $15, and information: (718) 707-1277. There is no Web site. JACKSON HEIGHTS, QUEENS, JUNE 9 AND 10 On June 9, nine private gardens will be open from noon to 4 p.m. The gardens are found in the interior courtyards of the 1920’s apartment buildings that make up the neighborhood. They include the Chateau, Elm Court, Hampton Court and Hawthorne Court. The largest gardens feature classical designs, with sitting areas, fountains and paths with columns. There will also be a display of historic photographs and student art, and an illustrated lecture on the history of Jackson Heights at 10:45 a.m. and 12:15 p.m. On June 10, a guided neighborhood tour will be offered starting at noon. Tickets for the guided tour must be reserved or purchased in advance. Tickets for one tour, $10; both, $15. All events take place or begin at the Community Church, 35th Avenue at 82nd Street. Information: (718) 565-5344 and MOUNT MORRIS PARK, HARLEM, JUNE 10 A tour from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. will feature several historic brownstones as well as new apartments and several places of worship. There will also be a guided tour in Marcus Garvey Park at 11 a.m. and guided tours of the neighborhood with John Reddick, a historian, at noon and 2 p.m. Tickets, $30, Pelham Fritz Community Center, West 122nd Street and Mount Morris Park West. Advance tickets, $25; or tour events and a reception, $40, and information: (212) 369-4241 and FLATBUSH, BROOKLYN, JUNE 10 Ten to twelve houses will be open for the 31st annual Victorian Flatbush house tour, from 1 to 6 p.m. The Flatbush area is home to four historic districts, with tree-lined streets and Craftsman, Victorian, Colonial Revival, Tudor and Queen Anne houses on large lots, with wrap-around porches and interiors boasting carved woodwork and patterned floors. Tickets, $20, at Temple Beth Emeth, 83 Marlborough Road (near Church Avenue). Advance tickets, $15, and information: (718) 859-3800 and PROSPECT HEIGHTS, BROOKLYN OCT. 14 Several residences, including Neo-Romanesque and Renaissance Revival townhouses from the second half of the 19th century, and at least one contemporary home, will be open from noon to 5 p.m. Tickets, $20, at the Forest Floor, 659 Vanderbilt Avenue (Prospect Place). Advance tickets, $15, and information: (718) 707-1277 and SEA CLIFF, MAY 20 A Sears kit house overlooking Hempstead Harbor is one of seven properties open from noon to 4 p.m. There will also be an 1880 Italianate house decorated with the owners’ collections of cranberry glass, bird prints and green Fire King glass objects. Tickets are $25. Advance purchase is suggested by May 13, by check with a self-addressed, self-stamped envelope, to Sea Cliff Landmarks Association, 19 Locust Place, Sea Cliff, N.Y. 11579. Tickets, if available on the day of the tour, at the village green at Sea Cliff and Central Avenues; (888) 216-6779. There is no Web site. LAUREL HOLLOW, COLD SPRING HARBOR, HUNTINGTON BAY AND CENTERPORT, MAY 23 A 1916 40-room mansion, with 14 fireplaces, ornate moldings and black walnut paneling in the living room, will be the centerpiece of a tour of five houses, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Tickets, to benefit the Family Service League of Long Island, $55, at the Thatched Cottage, 445 East Main Street (near Washington Avenue) in Centerport. Lunch, by reservation, is available for $25. Advance tickets, $50, and information: (631) 427-3700, extension 255 and SOUTHAMPTON, JUNE 9 AND 10 The theme of this year’s symposium and tour is photography and the garden. The symposium, on June 9, from 8:30 a.m. to 1 p.m., will be held at the , 25 Job’s Lane (Main Street). Five gardens on the East End, including one at the site of an 1850s hay barn that features dense perennial beds, native species and a wildflower field, will be open for a tour on June 10 from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Tickets: $175, $125 for members; (631) 283-2118, and BRIDGEHAMPTON, JULY 22 THROUGH SEPT. 3 There will be a show house to benefit Southampton Hospital. Open daily, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m. No children under six. Tickets, $30. A preview party will take place on July 21 at 6 p.m. Tickets are $250. More information, closer to the event, at (631) 745-0004 or Westchester and Putnam Counties GARRISON AND COLD SPRING, JUNE 3 Eight houses will be open from 11:30 a.m. to 5 p.m., including a house designed by Russel Wright’s companion, Joe Chapman, which has stunning Hudson River views. Tickets, including a box lunch, in advance only: $125; (845)424-3812 and PLEASANTVILLE, JUNE 4 The tour offered by the Neuberger Museum of Art will focus on the Usonia community, a 100-acre development designed by for middle-class families. The day will start with a lecture and light breakfast at 8:30 a.m. at the museum, which is on the campus of Purchase College, part of the State University of New York , 735 Anderson Hill Road, in Purchase. It will be followed by a guided tour of five houses in Usonia, including the three wholly designed by Wright. No children under 16. Tickets, in advance only, are $120 ($100 for museum members): (914) 251-6114 and FISHKILL, JUNE 9 Six houses and churches rich with Revolutionary War history will be open for the Silver Ribbon Tour, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tickets: $35, at 401 Route 52 (south of Interstate 84). Advance tickets: $35 ($30 for members of the Dutchess County Historical Society); (845) 471-1630 and GOSHEN, JUNE 16 Six private gardens will be open from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., including one with bird feeders, birdhouses, and plants that attract birds; a small walled garden; and the property of an 1853 mansion designed by Calvert Vaux, which still has some of its original plantings and where the owners will host a sculpture exhibition. Tickets, $35, will include lunch, a music performance and a display by the Mid-Hudson Orchid Society. Information: (845) 294-6225, or Orange County Tourism, at (845) 291-2136. There is no Web site. MONTGOMERY, DEC. 9 At least eight houses will be open in the historic area of Montgomery, which was settled in the early 18th century, from 1 to 5 p.m. A shuttle bus will be offered in case of bad weather. Tickets, in advance, $10; day of tour, $12. Inquires for ticket purchase by e-mail only, after Oct. 1, to RUMSON, THROUGH MAY 31 Scothigh Farm, a Colonial Revival house built in 1926 as a summer estate, will be the site of a show house to benefit the Visiting Nurse Association of Central Jersey. No children under 12. Open Tuesday through Sunday, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., at 142 Bingham Avenue (near Rumson Road). Admission: $35; $20 for 65 and older. Advance tickets: $25 before May 1; (732) 224-6791 and BOONTON, MAY 12 The Boonton Historical Society and Museum will sponsor a tour of 10 sites from 11:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. The tour will include an 1898 house with original pocket doors, fireplaces, plaster moldings and stair railings, along with new porch, kitchen cabinetry and remodeled top-floor bathroom, and St. John’s Episcopal Church, an 1863 structure with three stained glass windows by . Tickets, $25, at the museum, 210 Main Street (Route 202). Information: (973) 316-0976 or by e-mail to . There is no Web site. Next Article in Home & Garden (6 of 9) &#x00bb; Explore TimesSelect with a no-risk 14-day free trial. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. URBAN TACTICS; Garden City New Laws Crack Down on Urban Paul Bunyans LONG ISLAND JOURNAL; A Taste of Home, a Click and a Flight Away Trees Bind Angkor Temples in Perilous Grip Historic Buildings and Sites Next Article in Home & Garden (6 of 9) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard Narcotic Maker Guilty of Deceit Over Marketing Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Movie Review | '28 Weeks Later': The Satire Is Biting, and So Are the Zombies Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Prenatal Test 