ng Hudson River views. Tickets, including a box lunch, in advance only: $125; (845)424-3812 and PLEASANTVILLE, JUNE 4 The tour offered by the Neuberger Museum of Art will focus on the Usonia community, a 100-acre development designed by for middle-class families. The day will start with a lecture and light breakfast at 8:30 a.m. at the museum, which is on the campus of Purchase College, part of the State University of New York , 735 Anderson Hill Road, in Purchase. It will be followed by a guided tour of five houses in Usonia, including the three wholly designed by Wright. No children under 16. Tickets, in advance only, are $120 ($100 for museum members): (914) 251-6114 and FISHKILL, JUNE 9 Six houses and churches rich with Revolutionary War history will be open for the Silver Ribbon Tour, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tickets: $35, at 401 Route 52 (south of Interstate 84). Advance tickets: $35 ($30 for members of the Dutchess County Historical Society); (845) 471-1630 and GOSHEN, JUNE 16 Six private gardens will be open from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., including one with bird feeders, birdhouses, and plants that attract birds; a small walled garden; and the property of an 1853 mansion designed by Calvert Vaux, which still has some of its original plantings and where the owners will host a sculpture exhibition. Tickets, $35, will include lunch, a music performance and a display by the Mid-Hudson Orchid Society. Information: (845) 294-6225, or Orange County Tourism, at (845) 291-2136. There is no Web site. MONTGOMERY, DEC. 9 At least eight houses will be open in the historic area of Montgomery, which was settled in the early 18th century, from 1 to 5 p.m. A shuttle bus will be offered in case of bad weather. Tickets, in advance, $10; day of tour, $12. Inquires for ticket purchase by e-mail only, after Oct. 1, to RUMSON, THROUGH MAY 31 Scothigh Farm, a Colonial Revival house built in 1926 as a summer estate, will be the site of a show house to benefit the Visiting Nurse Association o