er, commissioned 200 chairs from the line, called Smoke, for the Gramercy Park Hotel. “It’s really the ultimate thing for any designer to have a solo exhibition at Moss,” said Mr. Baas, now 29. “What was so important about Moss was the exposure he gave to all these talented people from around the world,” said Mr. Schrager. “Without him, this whole phenomenon — this new wave of design consciousness in America — might not have happened.” Designers, of course, have not been the only ones to profit. In recent years Mr. Moss has expanded his business beyond the original shop at 146 Greene Street, first with a duplex addition next door, then with a design gallery beyond that, and most recently with the restaurant Centovini, appointed in high Mossian style, around the corner. This year, the Spanish designer Patricia Urquiola has remade the original shop into the two-story Moroso at Moss, a collaborative venture with the Italian furniture manufacturer Moroso, to open on May 19, and in July the gallery, newly connected to the shop, will be given over to retail space. Next month, Mr. Moss will open his first out-of-city branch, a 4,000-square-foot store in Los Angeles. According to Franklin Getchell, who shares ownership of the store with Mr. Moss, the businesses are projected to make $25 million this year. Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. CRITICAL SHOPPER; A Trip to the Gift Shop Is Like a Day at the Museum THE HUNT; A Firehouse Reinvented by Art FORAGING; BERLIN: MONDOS ARTS FRONT ROW; The New Palette of Gansevoort Retail Stores and Trade Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Th