http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10room.html?ex=1336449600&en=b1a004ae9a214db1&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	Room to Improve - New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 Simplicity goes a long way toward making a bathroom feel as if it is from another time. The most difficult part of the job may be undoing old decorating. Before you bring in new fittings, fixtures or furniture, take stock of what you have and remove ill-conceived flourishes. Vinyl flooring or carpet? Rip it out. Jaunty wallpaper? Tear it off. Skip to next paragraph If the tile is white, glossy and clean, you should leave it alone; that is the look you want. If it is colored or printed with images of seahorses, you have little choice but to replace it. As Barbara Sallick, co-founder and senior vice president of design at Waterworks, the high-end bathroom fixtures company, points out, “There are only a few things you can do if you’re stuck with a bubblegum-pink bathroom.” Once you have a relatively clean canvas, you can shift your attention to fixtures and fittings. The most important area is the sink. If you do nothing else, Ms. Sallick said, paint the base of the existing vanity white, replace the counter with a marble slab and install a new basin and fittings. If you have a run-of-the-mill metal medicine cabinet, she said, replace it with a wood unit like the Traditional Medicine Cabinet ($815 to $865) from Waterworks ( ) or the Cartwright Medicine Cabinet ($229 to $329) from Restoration Hardware ( Robin Standefer and Stephen Alesch, the principals of Roman and Williams ( ), a New York design firm, suggested replacing the old vanity unit with a washstand that leaves the plumbing exposed. They installed such a washstand for a client in Los Angeles, with a custom Industrial Base, above, from Urban Archaeology (starting at $1,670 at Where to put items you were storing under the sink? Ms. Standefer and Mr. Alesch suggested building shallow cabinets into the wall. For their client, they created mirrored units above the sinks, surrounded by floor-to-ceiling storage. Ms. Standefer recommended using a high-gloss paint, Hollandlac Brilliant from Fine Paints of Europe ($95 for 2 ½ liters or 2/3 gallon, ), in a cream color on all the woodwork to make it look “instantly sparkly, rich, shiny and washable.” That is important, Mr. Alesch said, because “old-school bathrooms look like you could scrub them down with a bucket of bleach and a huge brush.” When you are choosing hardware, don’t be afraid to buy taps that are separate from the faucet. The one-piece units that many remodelers use, Ms. Sallick said, “are so awful, and so telltale inexpensive.” Use a three-piece set instead, like the ones from the Waterworks Astoria line (from $985). It might also be worth visiting P. E. Guerin (212-243-5270 or ) at 23 Jane Street in Manhattan, one of the oldest decorative hardware manufacturers in the country. Prices for classic stock fittings, like the Beaded Group, start at about $2,000, and custom work is available as well. Glass dispensers like Restoration Hardware’s Grafton Clear Accessories ($39 to $49) and Sabon’s bath products ( ), which come in attractive glass containers, will help create a sense of luxury. Also, make sure your towels are inviting. “Ultimately, there is nothing as luxurious and old-world as beautiful towels hung really neatly on the towel bars,” Ms. Sallick said. Questions about décor may be sent by e-mail to . Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. Next Article in Home & Garden (4 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. PERSONAL HEALTH; A Simple Need, All Too Often Unmet The Year Without Toilet Paper Coming to Madison Square Park: Relief at a Quarter a Flush POSSESSED; Bathroom Reading, On the Wall Next Article in Home & Garden (4 of 9) &#x00bb; The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny The Curious Cook: The Five-Second Rule Explored, or How Dirty Is That Bologna? The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Highway Debris, Long an Eyesore, Grows as Hazard New York City Renters Cope With Squeeze Psychiatrists, Children and Drug Industry&#8217;s Role The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Genes Take Charge, and Diets Fall by the Wayside Fisher Is a Father First, and a Jazz Player Later Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Go to Complete List » Giuliani to Support Abortion Rights G.O.P. Moderates Warn Bush Iraq Must Show Gains Bush in Accord With Democrats on Trade Deals President Open to Benchmarks in Iraq Measure Gonzales Seems Confident He Will Stay, Officials Say Facebook to Offer Free Classifieds Role of F.B.I. Informer Draws Praise and Questions On Carrier in Gulf, Cheney Issues Warning to Iran Romney Works to Put Skeptics' Doubts to Rest Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » The new Broadway show Legally Blonde delivers "a nonstop sugar rush" Angela Lansbury in "Deuce" A trashy Tupperware lady hits the stage David Mamet to return to the theater of politics Find home & garden professionals in your area today In Home & Garden: View all Home & Garden Classifieds Post Your Ad Now! N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; No One Says ‘9/11.’ No One Needs To. Father and Son, Just Two More Soccer Fans The Rings of Giuliani The New York Times Company
