http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10qna.html	Garden Q.&A. - New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 Why are all my rhododendrons browning and looking lame? It’s not just my previously robust specimens; they’re fading all over Westchester County, N.Y. Make that all over the Northeast and beyond, where winter burn is affecting evergreens including rhododendrons, hollies and boxwoods. Last winter, warmth that lasted until January prevented plants from going dormant and increased water needs. Then the thirsty, tender plants were abruptly hit by fierce cold. Unprotected ground froze quickly, so no more water could penetrate. Leaves further dried by sun and wind turned brown. The branches are probably healthy, so prune only as needed for fullness and flowering. Your rhododendrons may also have shoot blight or dieback, said Bradley H. Roeller, manager of grounds and display gardens at the Institute of Ecosystem Studies in Millbrook, N.Y. Winter burn hits mostly the outer foliage, and although the leaves are brown they look otherwise normal, Mr. Roeller said. But if entire branches have deformed brown leaves, even deep within the plant, suspect contagious disease. Wait for a dry, windless day so spores do not spread, he advised. Then prune off all diseased branches, dipping the pruners in isopropyl alcohol to sterilize them between cuts. Can Neem Do It All? I keep hearing that neem is an organic gardener’s cure-all, deadly to pests and diseases but harmless to everything else. Can this be true? No. But it is not far off. Many foliage feeders are repelled by products derived from the tropical neem tree, and those eating neem-covered leaves often lose appetite and starve. Most of neem’s pesticidal punch comes from the compound azadirachtin, which disrupts insects’ growth as well as dampening their appetite. It can also be a fungicide. Used as directed, neem is harmless to mammals and birds, and little danger to beneficial insects. But it is bad for fish. And it usually requires frequent reapplication: the gardener must be an active partner for neem to deserve its sterling reputation. Sources for neem include Peaceful Valley Farm and Garden Supply, (888) 784-1722 or , and Extremely Green Gardening Company, Address questions by e-mail to . Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually. Next Article in Home & Garden (5 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Polly Hill Is Dead at 100; Tested Hardiness of Plants IN THE GARDEN; Must Tulips Wither as the Climate Changes? IN THE GARDEN; A Tree-Hugger Shows Her Affection With a Saw Next Article in Home & Garden (5 of 9) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Make your wedding a day to remember In the Weddings Directory: View All Paid Announcements Search Vendors & Services Post Your Paid Announcement N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
