. Next comes the most challenging part of her job: courting the homeowners. “I was an institutional bond salesperson for an investment bank, so I’m used to calling people and bugging them,” said Ms. Lindau, who added that she usually tried to appeal to people by pointing out how interesting their home was and by pitching the historical society as a worthy cause. THOUGH a lot of homeowners are house proud, many are a little daunted by the idea of a tour, according to Ms. Coultas. Those who feel their homes must look magazine perfect may demur, saying they’ll reconsider after their floors have been refinished or once they have redecorated. More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; Want to save this article?  Download the Times File Toolbar - get it now with TimesSelect. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. DAY TRIP; A Country Retreat Where Good Design Flourished HOUSE PROUD; For the Baron of Yonkers, a Gothic Revival DAY TRIPS; Antiques Among the Locust Trees New York Area Climbs Out of Recession New Castle Historical Society More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France 50% off Times delivery. Football's Greatest Games Commemorative N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10moss.html	Aspiring to the Throne - New York Times Aspiring to the Throne From left: Donna Alberico for The New York Times; Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times; Terrence McCarthy for The New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 LAST Friday afternoon, Jamie Gray, the owner of the Brooklyn design boutique Matter, stood in an empty storefront in Lower Manhattan, scraping away at a stubborn plastic UV filter that covered the front window. The work was punishing — “hopefully there won’t be any scratches or blood loss,” he said, though he ended up calloused and bleeding — and very time consuming, considering he had less than two weeks left until the opening of Matter’s new Manhattan branch. A lot of problems remained to be dealt with, including glass doors he had trouble mounting on the display cases, and the important shipment of Established & Sons furniture stuck in customs limbo. Skip to next paragraph Some Other Takes, From Coast to Coast, on Contemporary Design But Mr. Gray had been through worse in the last few months, he said. When he set out to find a Manhattan space in February, he was lucky. “I called the right agent on the right day,” he said, and found this storefront, which he decided he had to have. He was soon shaking hands on a deal for the property and envisioning an opening that would coincide with the design bacchanalia around the International Contemporary Furniture Fair in May. Two hours later the deal fell through. “For three weeks I was scrambling,” he said. “And then they changed their minds; I got the space. So it has a happy ending. Or a happy beginning, anyway.” Beyond the financial risk he is undertaking, Mr. Gray will face plenty of competition when he opens the store — meant to have a “more refined sensibility” than its Park Slope progenitor — on May 17, two days before the furniture fair starts at the Javits Convention Center. (The fair ends May 22.) Matter is just one of dozens of contemporary design shops that have opened around the country in the last few years, and most of those in New York will be vying for attention next week, hoping to use parties, exhibitions and other promotional events to attract the crowds that are coming to the fair. But there is one store that all of them will be measuring themselves against: Moss, the most visible and influential design boutique in America, the store that “changed the whole ground rules of what a design shop can be,” said Mayer Rus, a contributing editor at House & Garden. Murray Moss, who opened the SoHo store that bears his name in 1994, is widely acknowledged to be the king of high-design retailing in this country, at least by members of the New York and European design establishments. “He is a brilliant curator, shopkeeper, tastemaker,” said Ellen Lupton, the curator of contemporary design at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in New York, adding that he had reinvented the business with his approach to shopkeeping “as a major cultural undertaking.” From the beginning, Mr. Moss brought an extraordinarily well-attuned eye for what was fresh and exciting to the stocking of his shelves, and displayed his eclectic but painstakingly edited wares in an all-white, museum-like setting, behind glass or on raised platforms, with accompanying labels describing provenance. He promoted the work of emerging designers like Tord Boontje and Hella Jongerius the way gallerists promote young artists, even featuring them in solo exhibitions at the store. “He was extremely influential in showing the world that design is an undervalued market,” Mr. Rus said, “and that these are things that are worth our respect, attention and money.” The world listened. During the 2004 contemporary furniture fair, for example, Mr. Moss showed burnt-wood furniture by the Dutch designer Maarten Baas, who was just two years out of design school; a year later, commissioned 200 chairs from the line, called Smoke, for the Gramercy Park Hotel. “It’s really the ultimate thing for any designer to have a solo exhibition at Moss,” said Mr. Baas, now 29. “What was so important about Moss was the exposure he gave to all these talented people from around the world,” said Mr. Schrager. “Without him, this whole phenomenon — this new wave of design consciousness in America — might not have happened.” Designers, of course, have not been the only ones to profit. In recent years Mr. Moss has expanded his business beyond the original shop at 146 Greene Street, first with a duplex addition next door, then with a design gallery beyond that, and most recently with the restaurant Centovini, appointed in high Mossian style, around the corner. This year, the Spanish designer Patricia Urquiola has remade the original shop into the two-story Moroso at Moss, a collaborative venture with the Italian furniture manufacturer Moroso, to open on May 19, and in July the gallery, newly connected to the shop, will be given over to retail space. Next month, Mr. Moss will open his first out-of-city branch, a 4,000-square-foot store in Los Angeles. According to Franklin Getchell, who shares ownership of the store with Mr. Moss, the businesses are projected to make $25 million this year. Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. CRITICAL SHOPPER; A Trip to the Gift Shop Is Like a Day at the Museum THE HUNT; A Firehouse Reinvented by Art FORAGING; BERLIN: MONDOS ARTS FRONT ROW; The New Palette of Gansevoort Retail Stores and Trade Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France Make your wedding a day to remember In the Weddings Directory: View All Paid Announcements Search Vendors & Services Post Your Paid Announcement N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
