http://www.nytimes.com/pages/garden/index.html	Home & Garden - New York Times Aspiring to the Throne From left: Donna Alberico for The New York Times; Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times; Terrence McCarthy for The New York Times A growing number of small stores are challenging Murray Moss’s supremacy as the arbiter of design in America. Slide Show: The Moss Model Slide Show: Design Stores Related Article: Some Other Takes, From Coast to Coast, on Contemporary Design At Home With Charlie White Order and Chaos in a Single Heartbeat Anxiety’s children: a perfectly aligned household and disquieting art. It Takes a Hammer to Grow This Salad A tiny portable garden is the place to raise greens and herbs. How can I create a feeling of old-world luxury in my bathroom? Q. Why are all my rhododendrons browning and looking lame? It’s not just my previously robust specimens; they’re fading all over Westchester County, N.Y. Dream Home Diaries Blog "When all else fails, face the facts. And the fact was we needed to build a smaller house." Go to Dream Home Diaries» Dressing rooms in the Hamptons, reimagining cardboard, far outside the box, rare rugs and more. The modern slipper chair, as distinctive as ever. House Tours: Inviting Outsiders In By KATE STONE LOMBARDI At the height of house tour season, a look at one Chappaqua couple who agreed to allow scores of strangers into their home to benefit the local historical society. For the Curious, It’s Open House Season The 2007 season of show houses and house and garden tours runs through fall, with several events every weekend. Here’s a list of tours throughout the country. MOST POPULAR - STYLE Girth and Nudity, a Pictorial Mission Modern Love: My First Lesson in Motherhood In the Garden: It Takes a Hammer to Grow This Salad The Minimalist: A No-Frills Kitchen Still Cooks Clearly, Frankly, Unabashedly Disabled Fitness: A Healthy Mix of Rest and Motion The Incredible Flying Granny Nanny Fitness: The Yoga Therapist Will See You Now A Swee