http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/13Rhouse.html?ex=1336708800&en=ead8c72300f87f0a&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss	House Tours: Inviting Outsiders In - New York Times House Tours: Inviting Outsiders In Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This By KATE STONE LOMBARDI Published: May 13, 2007 Skip to next paragraph A Peek Inside a Beautiful Home Amble in (Take Off Your Shoes) For the Curious, It’s Open House Season Long Island, Westchester, Connecticut and New Jersey Go to Complete Coverage » Photographs by Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times The exterior of the Isles' 19th-century Italianate farmhouse. WHEN Betsy Isles received a phone call in early February asking if she would be willing to put her 19th-century Italianate farmhouse on a house tour, it all seemed comfortably far off: The tour date wasn’t until May. She would have plenty of time to get ready. The cause was a good one. Proceeds from the tour — tickets are $70 for members, $80 for nonmembers — would benefit the local historical society. Besides, Mrs. Isles and her husband, Chris, love their home. Fascinated by local history, they were willing to open up their house, where they have lived 15 years, to fellow history buffs. In fact, Mrs. Isles’s only initial concern about participating was that the upstairs of the house remained off limits to visitors; the idea of strangers peering into the rooms of her two teenagers was a bit much. Between then and now — the tour is just days away — the Isleses have spent months preparing for the big event. Mrs. Isles teaches art at Greenwich Country Day School in Greenwich, Conn. Her husband, the director of construction for a small real estate company in Manhattan, is good-natured, with a penchant for offbeat collections, like the African Mancala games and fanciful folk-art face jugs that are displayed in the house. Together they have been clearing clutter, patching ceilings, planting flowers and getting their house ready for the roughly 300 visitors they expect on Thursday. This is the height of the house tour season. May and June are prime time, but house tours — usually organized to raise money for charitable causes — have become so popular that they now extend through the fall. The Christmas season brings another, smaller round of tours of homes decorated for the holidays. The popularity of house tours seems to be driven by a combination of admiration and voyeurism. Visitors get a peek into beautiful homes they’ve always wanted to see. Some people are simply curious; others are looking for decorating ideas. Because the featured houses range from mansions interior-designed to the hilt to smaller homes of historical significance, reactions run the gamut from envy (sometimes mixed with a little cattiness) to genuine interest and inspiration. So many groups are running house tours these days that organizers can start to feel a little competitive. “You’re always looking for something to have on your house tour that might be a little different,” said Jennifer Coultas, president of the Boonton Historical Society and Museum in New Jersey, which was scheduled to hold its biannual tour yesterday. “There are just so many house tours out there that people might be wondering what you have that other people don’t have.” The tours may be ubiquitous, but planning them is not something organizers take lightly. The Isleses’ home is being featured on a tour of six homes, run by the New Castle Historical Society. From the initial scouting of the houses to the moment that the last visitors take off their paper booties (most homes have a no-shoes-allowed policy), hours of work, dozens of phone calls and countless e-mail messages have transpired to ensure that the event goes smoothly. Jane Lindau, co-chairwoman of the house tour committee for the historical society, began getting organized in November, culling houses from a continuing list she had been keeping of possible homes to feature. In choosing houses for the tour, she tries to balance style and period. Next comes the most challenging part of her job: courting the homeowners. “I was an institutional bond salesperson for an investment bank, so I’m used to calling people and bugging them,” said Ms. Lindau, who added that she usually tried to appeal to people by pointing out how interesting their home was and by pitching the historical society as a worthy cause. THOUGH a lot of homeowners are house proud, many are a little daunted by the idea of a tour, according to Ms. Coultas. Those who feel their homes must look magazine perfect may demur, saying they’ll reconsider after their floors have been refinished or once they have redecorated. More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. DAY TRIP; A Country Retreat Where Good Design Flourished HOUSE PROUD; For the Baron of Yonkers, a Gothic Revival DAY TRIPS; Antiques Among the Locust Trees New York Area Climbs Out of Recession New Castle Historical Society More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; A Giant Takes On Physics&#8217; Biggest Questions An Amputee Sprinter: Is He Disabled or Too-Abled? Napa Valley? Bordeaux? No, but Still Wine Country Books: Doctors Who Wield the Pen to Heal the Profession The Greatest Mystery: Making a Best Seller Gonzales Pressed Ailing Ashcroft on Spy Plan, Aide Says Your Money: A Contrarian on Retirement Says Wait Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog The Critical Years: Middle School Manages Distractions of Adolescence Basics: In Hive or Castle, Duty Without Power Go to Complete List » Atomic Agency Concludes Iran Is Stepping Up Nuclear Work Ground Zero Illnesses Clouding Giuliani's Legacy Sex, Drugs and Updating Your Blog Is It the Woman Thing, or Is It Katie Couric? Billions in Oil Missing in Iraq, U.S. Study Finds The Flight From Iraq In a New Role, Senator Clinton's Strategist in Chief Religious Groups Granted Millions for Pet Projects Obama Says He'd Roll Back Tax Cuts for the Wealthiest Army Career Behind Him, General Speaks Out on Iraq Go to Complete List » Go to Complete List » $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France 50% off Times delivery. More than $7 Trades. It’s Called Value & We Value You. N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/13Rhouse.html	House Tours: Inviting Outsiders In - New York Times House Tours: Inviting Outsiders In Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This By KATE STONE LOMBARDI Published: May 13, 2007 Skip to next paragraph A Peek Inside a Beautiful Home Amble in (Take Off Your Shoes) For the Curious, It’s Open House Season Long Island, Westchester, Connecticut and New Jersey Go to Complete Coverage » Photographs by Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times The exterior of the Isles' 19th-century Italianate farmhouse. WHEN Betsy Isles received a phone call in early February asking if she would be willing to put her 19th-century Italianate farmhouse on a house tour, it all seemed comfortably far off: The tour date wasn’t until May. She would have plenty of time to get ready. The cause was a good one. Proceeds from the tour — tickets are $70 for members, $80 for nonmembers — would benefit the local historical society. Besides, Mrs. Isles and her husband, Chris, love their home. Fascinated by local history, they were willing to open up their house, where they have lived 15 years, to fellow history buffs. In fact, Mrs. Isles’s only initial concern about participating was that the upstairs of the house remained off limits to visitors; the idea of strangers peering into the rooms of her two teenagers was a bit much. Between then and now — the tour is just days away — the Isleses have spent months preparing for the big event. Mrs. Isles teaches art at Greenwich Country Day School in Greenwich, Conn. Her husband, the director of construction for a small real estate company in Manhattan, is good-natured, with a penchant for offbeat collections, like the African Mancala games and fanciful folk-art face jugs that are displayed in the house. Together they have been clearing clutter, patching ceilings, planting flowers and getting their house ready for the roughly 300 visitors they expect on Thursday. This is the height of the house tour season. May and June are prime time, but house tours — usually organized to raise money for charitable causes — have become so popular that they now extend through the fall. The Christmas season brings another, smaller round of tours of homes decorated for the holidays. The popularity of house tours seems to be driven by a combination of admiration and voyeurism. Visitors get a peek into beautiful homes they’ve always wanted to see. Some people are simply curious; others are looking for decorating ideas. Because the featured houses range from mansions interior-designed to the hilt to smaller homes of historical significance, reactions run the gamut from envy (sometimes mixed with a little cattiness) to genuine interest and inspiration. So many groups are running house tours these days that organizers can start to feel a little competitive. “You’re always looking for something to have on your house tour that might be a little different,” said Jennifer Coultas, president of the Boonton Historical Society and Museum in New Jersey, which was scheduled to hold its biannual tour yesterday. “There are just so many house tours out there that people might be wondering what you have that other people don’t have.” The tours may be ubiquitous, but planning them is not something organizers take lightly. The Isleses’ home is being featured on a tour of six homes, run by the New Castle Historical Society. From the initial scouting of the houses to the moment that the last visitors take off their paper booties (most homes have a no-shoes-allowed policy), hours of work, dozens of phone calls and countless e-mail messages have transpired to ensure that the event goes smoothly. Jane Lindau, co-chairwoman of the house tour committee for the historical society, began getting organized in November, culling houses from a continuing list she had been keeping of possible homes to feature. In choosing houses for the tour, she tries to balance style and period. Next comes the most challenging part of her job: courting the homeowners. “I was an institutional bond salesperson for an investment bank, so I’m used to calling people and bugging them,” said Ms. Lindau, who added that she usually tried to appeal to people by pointing out how interesting their home was and by pitching the historical society as a worthy cause. THOUGH a lot of homeowners are house proud, many are a little daunted by the idea of a tour, according to Ms. Coultas. Those who feel their homes must look magazine perfect may demur, saying they’ll reconsider after their floors have been refinished or once they have redecorated. More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. DAY TRIP; A Country Retreat Where Good Design Flourished HOUSE PROUD; For the Baron of Yonkers, a Gothic Revival DAY TRIPS; Antiques Among the Locust Trees New York Area Climbs Out of Recession New Castle Historical Society More Articles in New York Region &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France More than $7 Trades. It’s Called Value & We Value You. 50% off Times delivery. Statue of Liberty, New York Harbor, 1905 N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/10/garden/10moss.html	Aspiring to the Throne - New York Times Aspiring to the Throne From left: Donna Alberico for The New York Times; Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times; Terrence McCarthy for The New York Times Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: May 10, 2007 LAST Friday afternoon, Jamie Gray, the owner of the Brooklyn design boutique Matter, stood in an empty storefront in Lower Manhattan, scraping away at a stubborn plastic UV filter that covered the front window. The work was punishing — “hopefully there won’t be any scratches or blood loss,” he said, though he ended up calloused and bleeding — and very time consuming, considering he had less than two weeks left until the opening of Matter’s new Manhattan branch. A lot of problems remained to be dealt with, including glass doors he had trouble mounting on the display cases, and the important shipment of Established & Sons furniture stuck in customs limbo. Skip to next paragraph Some Other Takes, From Coast to Coast, on Contemporary Design But Mr. Gray had been through worse in the last few months, he said. When he set out to find a Manhattan space in February, he was lucky. “I called the right agent on the right day,” he said, and found this storefront, which he decided he had to have. He was soon shaking hands on a deal for the property and envisioning an opening that would coincide with the design bacchanalia around the International Contemporary Furniture Fair in May. Two hours later the deal fell through. “For three weeks I was scrambling,” he said. “And then they changed their minds; I got the space. So it has a happy ending. Or a happy beginning, anyway.” Beyond the financial risk he is undertaking, Mr. Gray will face plenty of competition when he opens the store — meant to have a “more refined sensibility” than its Park Slope progenitor — on May 17, two days before the furniture fair starts at the Javits Convention Center. (The fair ends May 22.) Matter is just one of dozens of contemporary design shops that have opened around the country in the last few years, and most of those in New York will be vying for attention next week, hoping to use parties, exhibitions and other promotional events to attract the crowds that are coming to the fair. But there is one store that all of them will be measuring themselves against: Moss, the most visible and influential design boutique in America, the store that “changed the whole ground rules of what a design shop can be,” said Mayer Rus, a contributing editor at House & Garden. Murray Moss, who opened the SoHo store that bears his name in 1994, is widely acknowledged to be the king of high-design retailing in this country, at least by members of the New York and European design establishments. “He is a brilliant curator, shopkeeper, tastemaker,” said Ellen Lupton, the curator of contemporary design at the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in New York, adding that he had reinvented the business with his approach to shopkeeping “as a major cultural undertaking.” From the beginning, Mr. Moss brought an extraordinarily well-attuned eye for what was fresh and exciting to the stocking of his shelves, and displayed his eclectic but painstakingly edited wares in an all-white, museum-like setting, behind glass or on raised platforms, with accompanying labels describing provenance. He promoted the work of emerging designers like Tord Boontje and Hella Jongerius the way gallerists promote young artists, even featuring them in solo exhibitions at the store. “He was extremely influential in showing the world that design is an undervalued market,” Mr. Rus said, “and that these are things that are worth our respect, attention and money.” The world listened. During the 2004 contemporary furniture fair, for example, Mr. Moss showed burnt-wood furniture by the Dutch designer Maarten Baas, who was just two years out of design school; a year later, commissioned 200 chairs from the line, called Smoke, for the Gramercy Park Hotel. “It’s really the ultimate thing for any designer to have a solo exhibition at Moss,” said Mr. Baas, now 29. “What was so important about Moss was the exposure he gave to all these talented people from around the world,” said Mr. Schrager. “Without him, this whole phenomenon — this new wave of design consciousness in America — might not have happened.” Designers, of course, have not been the only ones to profit. In recent years Mr. Moss has expanded his business beyond the original shop at 146 Greene Street, first with a duplex addition next door, then with a design gallery beyond that, and most recently with the restaurant Centovini, appointed in high Mossian style, around the corner. This year, the Spanish designer Patricia Urquiola has remade the original shop into the two-story Moroso at Moss, a collaborative venture with the Italian furniture manufacturer Moroso, to open on May 19, and in July the gallery, newly connected to the shop, will be given over to retail space. Next month, Mr. Moss will open his first out-of-city branch, a 4,000-square-foot store in Los Angeles. According to Franklin Getchell, who shares ownership of the store with Mr. Moss, the businesses are projected to make $25 million this year. Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. CRITICAL SHOPPER; A Trip to the Gift Shop Is Like a Day at the Museum THE HUNT; A Firehouse Reinvented by Art FORAGING; BERLIN: MONDOS ARTS FRONT ROW; The New Palette of Gansevoort Retail Stores and Trade Next Article in Home & Garden (1 of 9) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France More than $7 Trades. It’s Called Value & We Value You. Find home & garden professionals in your area today In Home & Garden: View all Home & Garden Classifieds Post Your Ad Now! N.Y. / Region &#x00bb; Campaigning for History: F.D.R.’s Path Winemakers Take On Brazil’s Climate High Prices for Donor Eggs Stir Concerns Two Television Specials for Bob Barker The New York Times Company
